 D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D}, we have a ≤ sSup {a | ∃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D}\n      -- This is a placeholder for the actual proof\n      have h₁₀ : a ≤ sSup {a | ∃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D} := by\n        calc\n          a ≤ sSup {a | ∃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D} := by\n            -- Since x ∈ {a | ∃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D} and x ≤ a, we can use the fact that a ≤ sSup {a | ...}\n            sorry\n          _ = sSup {a | ∃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D} := by rfl\n      exact h₁₀\n  calc\n    sSup (decomposition_of_refinement R) = sSup (⋃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), D) := by rw [h₁]\n    _ = sSup {a | ∃ D ∈ (R : Set (Set α)), a ∈ D} := by rw [h₂]\n    _ = sSup S := by rw [h₃]",
      "is not `downSet (sSup D)`, unless it is downward closed, but it is not specified. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps each `a ∈ S` is in some `D` because `a = sSup D` implies that for any `d ∈ D`, `d ≤ a`, but not that `a ∈ D`.\n\nBut perhaps Lean expects that we assume that each `a ∈ D` if `a = sSup D`, but this is not stated in the assumptions. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps the problem was supposed to be `sSup (⋃ D ∈ R, D) = sSup S`, but with some additional hypotheses, such that for every `D ∈ R`, there exists `a ∈ S` such that `sSup D = a`. \n\nBut in that case, as above, we would have `sSup (⋃ D ∈ R, D) ≤ sSup S`, because for any `x ∈ ⋃ D ∈ R, D`, there exists `D ∈ R` with `x ∈ D`, and then for this `D`, there exists `a ∈ S` with `sSup D = a`, and hence `x ≤ sSup D = a ≤ sSup S`. \n\nBut to get `sSup S ≤ sSup (⋃ D ∈ R, D)`, we need that every `a ∈ S` is in `⋃ D ∈ R, D`, which is not true unless we assume it. \n\nBut perhaps the confusion arises from how the problem was translated. Perhaps in reality",
      "\n  have h₁ : sSup (decomposition_of_refinement R) = sSup S := by\n    apply le_antisymm\n    · -- Prove sSup (decomposition_of_refinement R) ≤ sSup S\n      apply sSup_le\n      intro x hx\n      simp only [decomposition_of_refinement, Set.mem_iUnion] at hx\n      obtain ⟨D, hD, hD'⟩ := hx\n      have h₂ : x ∈ D := hD'\n      have h₃ : sSup D ≤ sSup S := by\n        have h₄ : ∃! (D' : Set α), D' ∈ R ∧ sSup D = sSup D' := by\n          have h₅ : ∃! D' ∈ R, sSup D = sSup D' := by\n            -- Use the unique decomposition property to find a set D' in R with the same supremum as D\n            sorry\n          -- Simplify the existential to match the required form\n          sorry\n        -- Use the unique decomposition property to conclude that D is in R and thus x ∈ R\n        sorry\n      -- Use the fact that x ∈ D and sSup D ≤ sSup S to conclude x ≤ sSup S\n      sorry\n    · -- Prove sSup S ≤ sSup (decomposition_of_refinement R)\n      apply sSup_le\n      intro x hx\n      have h₂ : x ∈ S := hx\n      have h₃ : x ∈ decomposition_of_refinement R := by\n        -- Use the fact that S is covered by the sets in the decomposition\n        sorry\n      -- Since x ∈ decomposition_of_refinement R, we have x ≤ sSup (decomposition_of_refinement R)\n      sorry\n  exact h₁",
      "\n   Therefore, `sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D) ≤ sSup S`.\n\n   We need to prove that `sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D) = sSup S`. \n\n   But the other direction is: for each `a ∈ S`, we have that `a ≤ sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D)`, because there exists `D ∈ R.carrier` with `a = sSup D`, and `sSup D ≤ sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D)` (as `D ⊆ ⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D`).\n\n   Therefore, `sSup S ≤ sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D)`.\n\n   Combining these gives `sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D) = sSup S`.\n\n   Therefore, it seems that we do not need any assumptions on the distributivity of `α`, nor that it is bounded, except perhaps that it is a complete lattice (to use the supremums).\n\n   But the Lean problem statement has `[DistribLattice α]` and `[BoundedOrder α]`. \n\n   Actually, `BoundedOrder` might not be needed because we're taking supremums of all of `S`, which might not be a finite set. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we need it because we need that arbitrary unions are bounded? \n\n   Wait no, perhaps not. In particular, the `BoundedOrder` assumption would make sure that there are a top and bottom element, but we're not using that in our reasoning.\n\n   But perhaps in Lean, the statement of `sSup` requires that `S` is bounded? \n\n   No, in Lean, `sSup` is always defined in a complete lattice, even if the set is not bounded. \n\n   For instance, in `CompleteLattice`, the `sSup` operator is defined for any set. \n\n   Therefore, perhaps these extra typeclass assumptions are not needed. \n\n   However, perhaps they are due to the particular definition of `refinement`. \n\n   But in any case, it seems that in our case, we can avoid using them.\n\n   However, we need to be careful with the definitions, because perhaps they are relevant for other parts of the proof. \n\n   But in our case, we only need:\n   - For every `a ∈ S`, there exists `D ∈ R.carrier` with `a = sSup D`.\n   - For every `D ∈ R.carrier`, every element of `D` is less than or equal to some element of `S`.\n\n   Wait, no: in our reasoning, we used that if `x ∈ D`, then `x ≤ a` (since `a = sSup D`). And since `a ∈ S`, `x ≤ a ≤ sSup S`. \n\n   But actually, it's not necessary to have `a ≤ sSup S` because `S` is an arbitrary set in the complete lattice, and its supremum may not exist unless we assume that it is bounded. \n\n   Hmm, perhaps in Lean, the `sSup S` is always defined because `α` is a complete lattice. \n\n   So perhaps our reasoning holds. \n\n   So perhaps we do not need `BoundedOrder`. \n\n   The other assumption is `DistribLattice`, but we did not use that in our reasoning either. \n\n   But perhaps in Lean, it's part of the hypothesis for some reason. \n\n   In any case, in this step, we do not seem to need those assumptions. \n\n   So perhaps in Lean, the `sSup S` is always defined (as `α` is a complete lattice), and our proof can proceed without them. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we need them to ensure that all the intermediate supremums exist, but in Lean's `CompleteLattice` everything is covered.\n\n   Wait, perhaps the assumption that the lattice is distributive is not necessary here, but perhaps it's needed in other parts of the proof. \n\n   However, in this particular step, it seems we can proceed without it.\n\n   Perhaps the most straightforward approach is to show that:\n   - `sSup S ≤ sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D)` because for each `a ∈ S`, `a ≤ sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D)`.\n   - `sSup (⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D) ≤ sSup S` because every element in `⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D` is less than or equal to some element of `S`, and hence less than or equal to `sSup S`.\n\n   But perhaps for the second part, we need to note that if `x ∈ ⋃ D ∈ R.carrier, D`, then there exists some `D ∈ R.carrier` and some `x ∈ D`, and we have that `x ≤ sSup D = a ∈ S`, hence `x ≤ a ≤ sSup S`.\n\n   Here we used that `sSup D = a`, and hence `x ≤ a` (as `x ∈ D`). \n\n   Therefore, we get that every element in the union is less than or equal than some element of `S`, and therefore less than or equal than `sSup